snippet.textDisplay: I’ve been really sad about the death Kobe and those on the helicopter. However, yesterday my wife showed me a credible news source that Kobe Bryant went to catholic mass with his daughter and prayed. When I saw that post a deep sigh just blew out of me...Carolyn said “aww your happy!”  Truth is, I really am, because to say eternity is important is an understatement. Kobe was a great basketball player and man, and he has been in eternity for over two days now. His death bought the reality of life’s short time to everyone’s front door step. “Tomorrow is not promised” is now embodied in this unexpected event.  Love your children, love your wife, love your family and friends. Most importantly LOVE GOD. Our lives are too short and we have an opportunity to serve Him while we are alive, so let us do our BEST. Jesus lived for a short period of time and changed the entire world because God became a man and died for our sins. I’m so glad he did, so now we can be forgiven and live our lives for Him. Then when our date with death comes, we can see Jesu and be with Him forever. This is so important, because I want ALL of my family there with me! Friends, neighbors, the world, who so ever. Again, I am so happy to hear about Kobe’s  final day beginning with prayer to God. Mambamentality4Jesus 4Real

snippet.textDisplay: This is crazy to hear/see Jerry West like this. I'm 36 and I've always respected Mr. West (even though I'm a die-hard Clippers fan). His professionalism and staying private about personal businesses etc. He was genuinely an old school, tough as nails type! To see Mr. West open up like this, just shocks me. I know it's obviously due to Kobe's passing, but that just speaks high volume in itself, on how Mr. West loved and respected Kobe. My condolences go out to the Bryant family, friends and fans. Also, to the other 7 passengers and their loved one's, who sadly passed away. In great health, happy and bright future ahead, take care my fellow friends. #MambaOut 🎤

snippet.textDisplay: I would love to see what Jerry West saw in those workouts because when you evaluate players (especially as one who played) at this level, it's about what they do off the ball and how quickly they pick up information while processing on the court... the calm rhythm of how a player uses his skills to execute a play or possession is everything... Kobe had all those gifts at 16-17 and into the draft at 18... this is like a prodigy at the wing position so to see this was amazing.... People don't realize, Nick Van Exel and Eddie Jones were the backcourt for the Lakers; then to win a title you had Derek Fisher and Kobe replace them... along with Ron Harper coming over with Phil.... It was a huge risk for Jerry West to go with Kobe as a starter at the time because Eddie Jones was beloved in Los Angeles - he was the guy after Byron Scott during the Lakers rebuilding years along with Van Exel replacing Magic and creating a playoff mode back in Los Angeles. If Nick Van Exel and Eddie Jones were on any other team they would have kept them and those guys would have been a top back court in another city.... the Lakers were loaded like in 1998 and 1999.

snippet.textDisplay: So days have passed and seen interviews with men who are completely broken over this tragedy, the pain you can feel is absolutely heart breaking, but we have to be able to learn something from this otherwise great people will have died in vane. What I’m about to express is not being said to disrespect anybody, including the pilot, but we have to make changes. One of the greatest aviation interviews I’ve seen in my lifetime was with the Captain Who landed a commercial aircraft on the Hudson,  Chelsley Sullenberger, who stated in a interview that “No matter how many times I fly in or out of a particular location I always consult my charts to be able to identify hazards, geography of the landscape around the location, and secondary safe places to land in the event of a emergency”. The pilot of this helicopter clearly had no idea of the terrain he was in, a safe altitude that would keep him safely above, and lastly the mistake of flying into airspace he knew had zero visibility. But the level of responsibility doesn’t stop there. In a 2016 helicopter crash that also took people’s lives the FAA recommendation, that Terrain Collision & Avoidance (TCAS) be immediately installed on all commercial helicopters was merely slid under the carpets and conveniently forgotten about. The pilot at the center of this is dead, and therefore to hold him accountable for multiple mistakes is mute, but if we just dismiss this as just another “accident” and changes are not made then these families that have been affected by this tragedy will be for nothing. Kobe’s life after basketball morphed into so much more than just basketball, he was trying to bring so many things to so many people, somebody truly to look up to and make a difference in the lives of children and adults. I do not know the man personally, but to see the pictures of him and his daughter Gianna , who was killed along with him, breaks me down into tears. We have to do better. My thoughts and prayers are with all of the families who have been affected by this. ❤️

snippet.textDisplay: Things like that make me ponder about life and how real it is. You having all these projects/plans for the future. All this love, money, fame....now....out of nowhere, no warning, from a very exciting moment to a complete utter disaster. Imagine his wife just trying to fathom what just happened! Did she expect on monday her whole life change? news n everyone talking about her husband and daughter's death? If I was Kobe, now 7 foot deep under the dirt. All the money i made, friends, loved ones, fans, properties and ownerships is gone. All alone in this tombstone. By time, people will forget me. Now the quetion is, what's after that? Is that it? Am i just a rearranged of atoms? Things like this moment makes me believe hard in God. And there is an after life. And that's the good news. So what did i learn from this? Be like Kobe, be kind. Love your family. Help other people out. Appreciate God, and always worship him. That's what counts in the end. Anything else don't really matter. RIP I grew up watching Kobe! Feel even more bad because of his daughter. God made that happen, can't question that. God is Just and each of us has some time to live. And just like Kobe, we don't know when or how. Let's do our best to be good!
